g.text: In this study, we obtained belt or wire shaped TiO
particles to use as a negative electrode by a hydro-
thermal and heat treatment process. Ball milling process
was utilized to crush the synthesized TiO
(B) particles
into smaller sizes to facilitate TiO
(B)/C composites
fabrication. The effects of ball mill treatment on the
electrochemical performance of the TiO
(B) particles
were evaluated in terms of microstructure and phase
changes.
Experimental details
For preparing TiO
(B) powder, 0.1 M P25 powder was
at first put into 10 M aqueous NaOH solution, and
then the solution was hydrothermally heated at 180°C
for 24 hrs. The obtained particles were calcined at
450°C for 6 hrs in air, resulted in having TiO
phase with nanobelt of thin and long length. After
that ball-milling was conducted on TiO
(B), mate-
rials and electrochemical characterizations were car-
ried out using SEM (Scanning Electron Microscopy,
S-4700, Hitachi), XRD (X-Ray Diffraction, D/MAX
2500, Rigaku) and Raman spectroscopy (Renishow,
invia Raman Microscope). As the milling time in-
creased, particle size of TiO
(B) powders decreased
from 24 μm to 0.2 μm through a 300 rpm, 3 hrs
ball-milling. Here, the size was measured using PSA
(Particle Size Analyzer with laser scattering, Photal
ELS-800, Otsuka electronics).
Electrochemical properties were measured with R2032
coin-type cells. A metal lithium foil was used as the
anode. Composite electrodes were prepared by mixing
80 wt% TiO
(B) powders, 10 wt% conductive Super-P,
10 wt% SBR-CMC binder, and N-methylpyrrolidone
(NMP) solvent to form uniform slurry. A solution of
1 M LiPF6 dissolved in a mixture of ethylene carbonate
(EC) and dimethyl carbonate (DMC) (1:1 w/w) was used
as the electrolyte. The cells were charged and discharged
between 1.0 and 3.0 V by applying a constant current of
50 mAg
Results and discussion
TiO
(B) powders were synthesized by the heat treatment
of the rod or belt-shaped H-titanate powders at 450°C
for 6 hrs, which had been prepared by a hydrothermal
process. The combined process of the hydrothermal and
heat treatment has been used for the synthesis of TiO
(B) powders [11,12]. The synthesized TiO
(B) powders
were ball milled using a planetary type ball mill at a
fixed rotation speed of 300 rpm for up to 3 hrs to make
them smaller sizes. The changes of morphology and size
of the powders with the milling time were observed
under SEM as shown in Figure 1. The as-synthesized
TiO
(B) powders were observed from Figure 1(a) to
be long rod or belt shaped. The powders were broken
into smaller sizes after 1 hr ball milling (Figure1(b)).
